title: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
The legal parents at birth
chunks.html_content:
Surrogacy is legal in the UK, but if you make a surrogacy agreement it cannot be enforced by the law.

If you use a surrogate, they will be the child’s legal parent at birth.

If the surrogate is married or in a civil partnership, their spouse or civil partner will be the child’s second parent at birth, unless they did not give their permission.

Legal parenthood can be transferred by parental order or adoption after the child is born.

If there is disagreement about who the child’s legal parents should be, the courts will make a decision based on the best interests of the child.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Surrogacy agreements
chunks.html_content:
The intended parents and surrogate can record how they want the arrangement to work in a surrogacy agreement.

Surrogacy agreements are not enforceable by UK law, even if you have a signed document with your surrogate and have paid their expenses.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
Apply with a partner
chunks.html_content:
You must apply for a parental order or adoption if you want to become the legal parent of the child.

You can apply for a parental order with a partner or on your own.

One of you must be genetically related to the child - in other words, be the egg or sperm donor.

You must be one of the following:

  • married
  • civil partners
  • living as partners

You must also:

  • have the child living with you
  • reside permanently in either the UK, Channel Islands or Isle of Man

You must apply within 6 months of the child’s birth.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
Apply as an individual
chunks.html_content:
You must be genetically related to the child - in other words, be the egg or sperm donor.

You must also:

  • have the child living with you
  • reside permanently in either the UK, Channel Islands or Isle of Man

You can apply for a child of any age if you apply before 4 July 2019. From 4 July 2019 you must apply within 6 months of the child’s birth.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in England or Wales
chunks.html_content: You must fill in a ‘C51 application form for a parental order’ and take or send it to a family court.
chunks.plain_content:
Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in England or Wales
You must fill in a ‘C51 application form for a parental order’ and take or send it to a family court.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in England or Wales
chunks.html_content: You do not have to use your local family court, but you’ll need to explain why if you do not.
chunks.plain_content:
Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in England or Wales
You do not have to use your local family court, but you’ll need to explain why if you do not.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in England or Wales
chunks.html_content:
You’ll need to provide the child’s full birth certificate and will also be charged a court fee of £232.

The court will then set a date for the hearing and issue you with a ‘C52 acknowledgement form’ that you must give to the child’s legal parent, in other words, your surrogate.

The surrogate and anyone else who’s a parent of the child must agree to the parental order by filling in form A101A.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Parental orders
How to apply in Scotland or Northern Ireland
chunks.html_content:
The process is different if you live in Scotland or Northern Ireland.

In Scotland, contact the Court of Session or Sheriff Court.

In Northern Ireland, contact the Courts and Tribunals Service.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Adoption
chunks.html_content: If neither you or your partner are related to the child, adoption is the only way you can become the child’s legal parent.
chunks.plain_content:
Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Adoption
If neither you or your partner are related to the child, adoption is the only way you can become the child’s legal parent.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
chunks.html_content: If your surrogate gives birth abroad, you can only apply for a parental order if you and your partner are living in the UK.
chunks.plain_content:
Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
If your surrogate gives birth abroad, you can only apply for a parental order if you and your partner are living in the UK.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
chunks.html_content: If the child is not a UK or EU national, they will need a visa to enter the UK during this process.
chunks.plain_content:
Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
If the child is not a UK or EU national, they will need a visa to enter the UK during this process.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
chunks.html_content:
Using a surrogate abroad can be complicated because different countries have different rules. You may want to get legal advice or contact The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority for more information.

You can also read about returning to the UK with your child.

heading_context: Surrogacy: legal rights of parents and surrogates
Surrogates
chunks.html_content:
You and your partner may be eligible for adoption pay and leave and paternity pay and leave if you use a surrogate.

If you’re not eligible for paid leave, you may be able to take parental leave or annual leave.

Every pregnant employee has the right to 52 weeks’ maternity leave and to return to their job after this.

What a surrogate does after the child is born does not affect their right to maternity leave.
